{"key":"processedPost-6163684","value":{"id":6163684,"first":6163464,"last":6164274,"when":1160705443,"utime":"10/13/06 05:10 AM","cleanedPost":"soaking in the refrigerator overnight is not cold shocking, nor is lowering the temperature to 70.  70 is within the optimum fruiting range and doesn't shock, which is bad for tropical species.  70F might help to <i>stimulate</i> pinning, but it doesn't <i>shock</i>.<br />'Cold shocking' is for cold weather species and takes five to seven days at the reduced temperature, not overnight.<br />You should soak in the refrigerator to avoid bacteria buildup in the anaerobic environment under water.  Peroxide breaks down within minutes in the presence of organic material such as a substrate, so is ineffective for an overnight soak.  Rinse the substrates under running water both before and after the soak.<br />RR"}}